e Rosenthal-Schneider: A woman interprets Albert Einstein |encyclopedia=Einsteins Kolleginnen – Physikerinnen gestern und heute [Einstein's (female) colleagues: (Women) physicists yesterday and today] |url=http://www.ecwt.eu/digitalcity/servlet/PublishedFileServlet/AAAAVJED/Gender-im-Einsteinjahr.pdf |year=2005 |pages=10–13 |isbn=978-3933476081 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Jagdish Mehra|author2=Helmut Rechenberg|title=The" Probability Interpretation and the Statistical Transformation Theory, the Physical Interpretation, and the Empirical and Mathematical Foundations of Quantum Mechanics: 1926 – 1932|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media, 2000|isbn=9780387989716|page=v|edition=illustrated|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CuOtQ4WjCP0C&pg=PR5&dq=Ilse+Rosenthal-Schneider#v=onepage&q=Ilse%20Rosenthal-Schneider&f=false|date=25 August 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Stephen G. Brush|title=Prediction and Theory Evaluation: The Case of Light Bending|journal=Science|volume=246|issue=4934|pages=1124–9|jstor=1704755|subscription=yes|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science|bibcode=1989Sci...246.1124B|year=1989|doi=10.1126/science.246.4934.1124|pmid=17820957}}</ref> Rosenthal-Schneider earned a PhD in philosophy in 1920 at the [[University of Berlin]], where she first met Albert Einstein. After leaving [[Nazi Germany]] and emigrating to Australia in 1938, she became a tutor in the German department at the [[University of Sydney]] in 1945 and taught [[History of science|history]] and [[philosophy of science]].<ref>Encyclopedia of Australian Science http://www.eoas.info/biogs/P003165b.htm</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Physics|url=http://hsc.csu.edu.au/physics/core/implementation/9_4_2/942net.html|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In the 1940s and 1950s, she exchanged a series of letters with Albert Einstein about philosophical aspects of physics, such as [[theory of relativity]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Hens, eggs, elephants and fear of stupid questions|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-24859359.html|subscription=yes|via=[[HighBeam]]|work=The Irish Times|date=5 October 2006}}</ref> [[Physical constant|fundamental constants]] and physical reality.<ref>Begegnungen mit Einstein, von Laue, und Planck (Vieweg Verlag 1988) by Ilse Rosenthal-Schneider, English edition: Reality and Scientific Truth : Discussions with Einstein, von Laue, and Planck (Wayne State Univ Pr, 1910)</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Susan S. Lukesh|title=Email and potential loss to future archives and scholarship|url=http://firstmonday.org/ojs/index.php/fm/article/view/692/602|accessdate=14 September 2014|date=6 September 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=I. Bernard Cohen|title=Albert Einstein: Philosopher-Scientist by Paul Arthur Schilpp|page=77|jstor=226691|subscription =yes|publisher=[[The University of Chicago]] Press on behalf of [[The History of Science Society]]|volume=42}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Max Jammer|title=Einstein and Religion: Physics and Theology|publisher=Princeton University Press, 2011|isbn=9781400840878|page=53|edition=reprint}}</ref> She remained in contact with Einstein through correspondence until the death of Einstein in 1955.<ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Albert B. Stewart|title=Reality and Scientific Truth by Ilse Rosenthal-Schneider|jstor=4611136|publisher=Antioch Review, Inc.|subscription =yes|volume=40}}</ref>
