{{italic title}}
'''''Zazen gi''''' ({{CJKV|j=坐禪儀}}), also known in various English translations such as '''''The Standard Method of Zazen''''' or '''''Principles of Zazen''''', is a book of the [[Shōbōgenzō]] by the 13th century [[Sōtō]] [[Zen]] monk [[Eihei Dōgen]]. The book appears tenth in the 75 fascicle version of the [[Shōbōgenzō]], and it is ordered 58th in the later chronological 95 fascicle "''Honzan'' edition".<ref name=textual>{{citation|last=Heine|first=Steven|title=Dōgen: Textual and Historical Studies|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2012|pages=27, 39|isbn=978-0-19-975447-2}}</ref> It was presented to his students in the eleventh month of 1243 at Yoshimine shōja (吉峰精舍), a small temple where Dōgen and his sangha practiced briefly following their sudden move to [[Echizen Province]] from their previous temple [[Kōshōhōrin-ji]] earlier in the same year and before the establishment of [[Eihei-ji]]. Unlike other books of the Shōbōgenzō, it is not as much a commentary on classical [[Chan Buddhism|Chinese Chan literature]] as it is a guide for the practice of [[zazen]]. The title comes from earlier Chinese texts of the same name and purpose, with a well known example found in the ''[[Chanyuan Qinggui|Chanyuan qinggui]]'', from which Dōgen quotes extensively. His more famous ''[[Fukan zazengi]]'', as well as ''[[Eihei shingi]]'''s ''Bendoho'', also owe much to this Chinese text and are thus closely related to the Shōbōgenzō's ''Zazen gi''.<ref name=bielefeldt>{{citation|last=Bielefeldt|first=Carl|title=Kobutsushin: Introduction|year=2005|publisher=Sotoshu Shumucho|url=http://stanford.edu/group/scbs/sztp3/translations/shobogenzo/translations/zazengi/zazengi.intro.html}}</ref><ref name=Gudo>{{Citation| last1 =Nishijima|first1=Gudo|last2=Cross|first2=Chodo|authorlink1=Gudo Nishijima|year = 2008| title = Master Dogen's Shōbōgenzō| volume=3|pages=225– 227|publisher = Numata Center for Buddhist Translation and Research| isbn=978-1-886439-37-5}}</ref> 
